#: templates/faq.html:411 templates/toc.html:22
msgid "Line Colors"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:412
msgid ""
"A public transport route is displayed in the wrong color. Where do the "
"line colors come from?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:416
msgid ""
"I wanted to avoid creating yet another database collecting the "
"information about which colors every public transport line in Austria "
"uses, as this would just make everyone else's job harder in the future if"
" they want to integrate it into their project. So instead, I tried to "
"generate the mapping from GTFS-ID (which describes a specific route) "
"using a mix of OpenStreetMap, the <a "
"href=\"https://ptna.openstreetmap.de/results/AT/index.php\">PTNA</a> "
"project and some simple hard-coded rules (e.g. all trams in Vienna have "
"the same color)."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:427
msgid ""
"This is not yet complete, but it is already working pretty well. And it "
"also means that any new colors can just be added to or corrected in OSM "
"by anyone and when I re-run the import on the latest data the table will "
"be corrected."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:435
msgid "The full table can be found here:"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:441
msgid ""
"(The table is a lua script for now as this is what makes applying the "
"data in MOTIS most easily. But if anyone is interested I can also add it "
"as a CSV or in any other format)"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:448
msgid ""
"And more information about how exactly the data is sourced can be found "
"here:"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:455
msgid ""
"In short: If the color of a route is shown correctly in PTNA, but not in "
"route.lw1.at, then this is a mistake on my end (and please contact me "
"about it). If not, then the data is missing in OSM and you can add it "
"there."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:462 templates/toc.html:27
msgid "UI"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:464
msgid "Is there a dark theme?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:466
msgid ""
"Yes, it might not be optimally displaying everything, but you can access "
"it at <a href=\"https://route.lw1.at/?dark\">route.lw1.at/?dark</a>."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:471
msgid "Is there a simpler UI to find routes?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:473
msgid ""
"If you just want to find a connection and don't want to load the full UI "
"on a slow internet connection, you can use the great lite UI at <a "
"href=\"https://lite.route.lw1.at/\">lite.route.lw1.at</a> by <a "
"href=\"codeberg.org/jbb/motis-frontend-basic\">jbb</a>."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:478 templates/toc.html:32
msgid "Transfer/Indoor Routing"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:480
msgid "How does indoor routing work?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:483
msgid ""
"If the paths, stairs and elevators inside of public transport stations "
"are mapped correctly in OSM, MOTIS is able to route the exact path one "
"needs to walk to exits or platforms."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:488
msgid ""
"When zooming in closely, you can also select a floor level in the top "
"right to only show paths on this level."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:492
msgid ""
"You can look at Karlsplatz in Vienna for an example of more complex "
"indoor routing."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:496
msgid "How can I use accessible routing and avoid stairs/escalators?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:498
msgid ""
"If you select \"accessible transfers\" in the options, MOTIS will avoid "
"stairs and escalators and instead use elevators to find the fastest way "
"to a goal. As this data is often slightly imprecise in OSM, it is "
"possible that MOTIS will show very suboptimal routes if the \"obvious\" "
"route does not seem possible in the OSM data."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:505 templates/toc.html:37
msgid "Realtime Data"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:507
msgid ""
"I can see the location of trains/buses/etc. on the map. Is that their "
"real location?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:510
msgid ""
"As I am not yet using any realtime data (<a href=\"#realtime-info\">see "
"below</a>) all positions are estimated from the published schedules. "
"Nevertheless, assuming there are no unexpected delays, etc., the "
"positions should still give a good impression of the current locations of"
" public transport in Austria."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:520
msgid "What realtime information is available?"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:522
msgid ""
"Realtime public transport information (such as delays, cancelations, "
"etc.) on top of the existing schedules is possible by following a GTFS-RT"
" feed that shares this information in a structured format (and linked to "
"the routes of the static schedule)."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:528
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, to my knowledge (as of April 2026), there is no official "
"GTFS-RT feed for any public transport in Austria. There seem to be plans "
"and initiatives to get e.g. ÖBB to publish their realtime information in "
"a structured way, but this still seems to be in the future. (See this "
"freedom of information request for more details: <a "
"href=\"https://fragdenstaat.at/anfrage/zugang-zu-dynamischen-"
"echtzeitdaten-api-schnittstelle/\">fragdenstaat.at/anfrage/zugang-zu-"
"dynamischen-echtzeitdaten-api-schnittstelle</a>)"
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:538
msgid ""
"I had an idea to provide at least some rough realtime data for some major"
" ÖBB train connections by writing my own program that makes irregular "
"requests to fahrplan.oebb.at. This would essentially be reinventing a "
"more basic version of <a href=\"https://github.com/derhuerst/hafas-gtfs-"
"rt-feed\">derhuerst/hafas-gtfs-rt-feed</a> and would potentially only "
"require a very small number of requests to have data for all major "
"express train connections. However, after implementing most of it, I "
"realized that connecting this information to the corresponding entries in"
" the train schedules was far more complex than anticipated (even when "
"using Motis itself to guess the most likely route a specific train is "
"currently following). Therefore, I will set this aside until more "
"official data sources become available where realtime info is more "
"closely linked to the static schedules."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:556
msgid ""
"The closest thing to an official Open Data endpoint for realtime data I "
"know of, is the <a href=\"https://www.data.gv.at/datasets/cfba4373-a654"
"-3e0b-80f8-348738169f95?locale=de\">Wiener Linien "
"Echtzeitinformationen</a>."
msgstr ""

#: templates/faq.html:561
msgid ""
"But this does not contain any realtime information about specific "
"vehicles or routes, but \"just\" the textual warnings about current "
"disruptions. Additionally, the Line and Station-IDs don't match those in "
"the static schedule, but because there is a public dataset of these "
"Station IDs, it is possible to match them up almost flawlessly."
msgstr ""

